Efficiency analysis:

The time complexity of this solution is O(n^2), where n is the length of the string num. This is because we iterate over the string num twice: once for each pair of digits to compare their positions.

Space complexity is O(1) since we only use a single integer variable for result and swaps.

Explanation:

The solution iterates through the string num twice, comparing adjacent digits and updating the result and swaps count accordingly. The outer loop ensures that we only consider digits that are greater than the current digit being checked. The inner loop compares each digit with the current digit being checked. If a digit is found to be greater, the result is updated, and a swap is performed. This process continues until all digits have been checked.

The solution is efficient because it only requires O(n^2) time complexity and O(1) space complexity.

